(674, 'The State aims to leverage its existing clinical coverage policies and enhance access for providers and beneficiaries to services delivered via telemedicine by:\nâ€¢ Increasing provider awareness, education and training by supporting the establishment of an independent, statewide telemedicine alliance;. (State is seeking $5 million in federal funds for start-up costs for the telemedicine alliance)                                                                                                                            â€¢ North Carolina seeks expenditure authority (up to $80 million) to establish a â€œTelemedicine Innovation Fundâ€ to\nsupport provider-PHP collaborations that test evidence-based telemedicine initiatives aligned with the Stateâ€™s\nquality strategy goals, such as chronic disease management, wellness promotion and high-value care.21      (e.g., pilots)', NULL, 'North Carolina Medicaid and NC Health Choice: Amended Section 11115 Demonstration Waiver Application', 'https://files.nc.gov/ncdhhs/documents/files/NC-Amended1115DemonstrationWaiverApplication_GovCooperLtr_20171120.pdf?PpFJgK3wwi.BFkdX4t6e5L8oSXK6_c8B', '1', 189, 1, 24, '1', '2018-11-12 12:08:57', '2018-11-22 16:41:50'),
(675, 'Managed care organizations will be encouraged to support the use of telemedicine as a tool for ensuring access to needed services; allowed to provide access to a service that is not available within the plan\'s network; be permitted to leverage telemedicine in meeting DHHSâ€™ network adequacy standards; be encouraged to implement pilots that test additional telemedicine strategies and will invite PHPs to propose innovative pilots related to telemedicine in their responses to DHHSâ€™ Medicaid managed care procurement.', 'State\'s Medicaid program is FFS and is transitioning to managed care. ', 'Strategic Plan for Improvement of Behavioral Health Services: Report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Service and Fiscal Research Division. North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services  ', 'https://files.nc.gov/ncdhhs/documents/files/SL%202016-94%2C%20Sect.%2012F.10%20and%20SL%202017-57%20Sect.%2011F.6%20Strategic%20Plan%20for%20Improvement%20of%20Behavioral%20Health%20Services%20.pdf?4SjY_N4YP3KadXXEuEOhGa0xQzXdBJwd', '1', 189, 1, 25, '1', '2018-11-12 12:08:57', '2018-11-22 16:41:50'),
(676, 'Law :  "Telehealth"\n(1) Means the use of interactive audio, video, or other telecommunications\ntechnology that is used by a health care provider or health care facility at a distant site to deliver health services at an originating site and that is delivered over a secure connection that complies with the requirements of\nstate and federal laws.\n\n(2) Includes the use of electronic media for consultation relating to the health\ncare diagnosis or treatment of a patient in real time or through the use of store-and-forward technology.\n\n(3) Does not include the use of audio-only telephone, electronic mail, or facsimile transmissions. \n\n Medicaid:  "Telemedicine" is the use of interactive audio-video equipment to link practitioners and patients at different sites. Telemedicine involves two collaborating provider sites: an â€œoriginating siteâ€ and a â€œdistant siteâ€. The client/patient is located at the originating site and the practitioner enrolled with ND Medicaid is located at the distant provider site to provide those professional services allowed/reimbursed by ND Medicaid. ', NULL, 'North Dakota Century Code - Accident and Health Insurance \n26.1-36-09.15 \n\nNorth Dakota Medicaid Medical Policy \nSFN 85 (6-9-2010)  ', 'http://www.legis.nd.gov/cencode/t26-1c36.pdf#nameddest=26p1-36-09p15 |\n\nhttp://www.nd.gov/dhs/services/medicalserv/medicaid/docs/telemedicine-policy.pdf ', '0', 190, 1, 1, '1', '2018-11-12 12:08:57', NULL),
