(697, 22, 'MI', 'Question', 'Does the state Medicaid program apply any geographic restrictions to telemedicine encounters?', 'No', 'Provider manual indicates that telemedicine should be used primarily when travel is prohibitive for the\nbeneficiary or there is an imminent health risk justifying immediate medical need for services.', 'Michigan Medicaid Provider Manual', 'http://www.mdch.state.mi.us/dch-medicaid/manuals/MedicaidProviderManual.pdf', '2018-11-26 08:21:03', '2018-11-26 08:21:03'),
(698, 22, 'MI', 'Question', 'Does the state Medicaid program limit coverage and reimbursement for telemedicine to a prescribed set of health conditions or services?', 'Yes', 'Covered telemedicine services:\n â€¢ ESRD-related services\nâ€¢ Behavior change intervention\nâ€¢ Behavioral Health and/or Substance Use Disorder Treatment\nâ€¢ Education Services, Telehealth\nâ€¢ Inpatient consultations\nâ€¢ Nursing facility subsequent care\nâ€¢ Office or other outpatient consultations\nâ€¢ Office or other outpatient services\nâ€¢ Psychiatric diagnostic procedures\nâ€¢ Subsequent hospital care\nâ€¢ Training service â€“ Diabetes (Refer to the Diabetes Self-Management Education (DSME) Training Program subsection in the Hospital Chapter for specific program requirements)\n\n"Where face-to-face visits are required (such as ESRD and nursing facility related services), the telemedicine service may be used in addition to the required face-to-face visit, but cannot be used as a substitute. There must be at least one face-to-face hands-on visit (i.e., not via telemedicine) by a physician, nurse practitioner, or physicianâ€™s assistant per month to examine the vascular site for ESRD services. The initial visit for nursing facility services must be face-to-face."', 'Michigan Medicaid Provider Manual', 'http://www.mdch.state.mi.us/dch-medicaid/manuals/MedicaidProviderManual.pdf', '2018-11-26 08:21:03', '2018-11-26 08:21:03'),
